<!-- FAQ SECTION -->
<div class="pb-faq-section" id="pb-faq-section">
    <h2 class="pb-faq-heading">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="pb-faq-item" id="pb-faq-0">
        <button class="pb-faq-trigger" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="pb-faq-answer-0"
                onclick="pbToggleFaq(this, 'pb-faq-answer-0')">
            <span>What is the difference between AI activity and AI ROI?</span>
            <svg class="pb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="pb-faq-answer" id="pb-faq-answer-0" role="region" hidden>
            <p>AI activity is what most dashboards report: tasks completed, hours saved, error rates reduced, adoption percentages. These tell you the AI is running. AI ROI is what those activities convert into: revenue generated, deals closed, cycle time compressed to a measurable business outcome. An AI tool can be producing high activity metrics and zero ROI if the time it saves does not get redirected into revenue-producing work.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pb-faq-item" id="pb-faq-1">
        <button class="pb-faq-trigger" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="pb-faq-answer-1"
                onclick="pbToggleFaq(this, 'pb-faq-answer-1')">
            <span>Why do 95% of AI implementations fail to generate measurable P&amp;L impact?</span>
            <svg class="pb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="pb-faq-answer" id="pb-faq-answer-1" role="region" hidden>
            <p>MIT's 2025 review of 300+ publicly disclosed AI implementations found only 5% generated millions in measurable P&amp;L impact. The other 95% produced efficiency and usage metrics that did not translate to business outcomes. The structural reason: most organizations deploy AI against general goals like "productivity" rather than tying each implementation to one specific, measurable business metric with a before-and-after target.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pb-faq-item" id="pb-faq-2">
        <button class="pb-faq-trigger" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="pb-faq-answer-2"
                onclick="pbToggleFaq(this, 'pb-faq-answer-2')">
            <span>What hidden costs should I include in AI ROI calculations?</span>
            <svg class="pb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="pb-faq-answer" id="pb-faq-answer-2" role="region" hidden>
            <p>Four costs are routinely understated: data preparation (typically 25-40% of total project cost), integration work with legacy systems, ongoing maintenance and retraining as models drift, and a probability-weighted cost of failure. With 85% of AI projects stalling before production and average repair costs around $710,000, the expected cost of failure is not negligible. When these are included, many AI ROI cases that looked positive become neutral or negative.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pb-faq-item" id="pb-faq-3">
        <button class="pb-faq-trigger" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="pb-faq-answer-3"
                onclick="pbToggleFaq(this, 'pb-faq-answer-3')">
            <span>What is the difference between renting AI and building an AI partnership?</span>
            <svg class="pb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="pb-faq-answer" id="pb-faq-answer-3" role="region" hidden>
            <p>Renting AI means accessing a generic capability for a monthly fee. The AI does not get better at your specific work over time. Building an AI partnership means the AI accumulates understanding of your organization, priorities, and standards - it becomes an appreciating asset rather than a recurring expense. The World Economic Forum documented a 3x performance advantage for augmentation approaches over automation-only deployments, and that gap is largely explained by depth of working relationship.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

